<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-412-118  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 412 118.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Robotics Today  Fall 1989 v2 n3 p1(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Applying robots in nontraditional roles.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Knape, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Product liability and safety are the major issues in developingnontraditional robotic applications that include fields such ashealth, human services, nuclear and electric power, agriculture,food, construction, underwater, space and the military.andP;  Mobility,artificial intelligence, semi-autonomy, the ability to sense andhigh-level judgment are some of the requirements for futurerobotic applications.andP;  The traditional criteria of return oninvestment, quality and throughput must also be met.andP;  Roboticapplications have the potential for improving the quality of lifefor handicapped and elderly people and have a sound justificationfor working in environments that may be hazardous to humans.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     RobotsRobotics IndustryArtificial IntelligenceTrendsForecastingProduct LiabilitySafetyReliability.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>